ref: Jour: Physical Review, Vol.175, Issue.4, p.1330 (1968)
title: Fast-photoneutron spectra due to 55-85-MeV photons.

x4freetext: Fast-photoneutron spectra due to 55-85-MeV photons.

x4codes.hlp: Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Troy, NY, United States of America

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Vol.175, Issue.4, p.1330 (1968)

x4codes.hlp: Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Troy, NY, United States of America

x4freetext: . A 0.010-in.-thick tantalum foil was used.
Solid samples were circular disks of 3/4 in. or 1 in.
diam.  oriented so that the disk axis coincided with
the photon beam axis.  Disk thicknesses were 1/8 in.
or 3/16 in.  for heavier nuclei (z>20) and between 1
and 2 2 in.  for lighter elements.  Water and liquid
nitrogen in thin-walled  aluminium  containers  were
used  as  the  samples for the studies of oxygen and
nitrogen.
Flight  path  =  100  m,  time resolution = 0.4
ns/m.
.Liquid scintillator   tank   of   5   in.  in
thickness and 20 in.  in diameter  viewed  by  seven
Philips 58 AVP photomultipliers was used.
Energy spectra were corrected for:
(a) the photon attenuation in the samples,
(b) the scattering of the outgoing neutrons in the
samples,
(c) the detector efficiency.
The quasideuteron model was used.
Energy spectra of fast  photoneutrons  from  eighteen
elements were measured.  Measurements of the spectra
from each target at bremsstrahlung energies of  both
55  and  85  MeV  permitted  extraction  of  neutron
difference  spectra  effectively  due   to   photons
between 55 and 85 MeV.
Difference spectra were obtained for neutron energies
greater  than  10  MeV.  The  experimental data were
compared to the  predictions  of  the  quasideuteron
model  with  secondary-neutron  effects estimated by
Monte  Carlo  calculations.   Good   agreement   was
obtained  for  the absolute-neutron-production cross
sections  and  the  shapes  of  the  neutron  energy
spectra over the range of targets studied.
Compiled in the SCJAD  of  Saratov  State
University.
SUBENTs   26,27   rearranged  to  SUBENTs
Corrected by SD and VV: new date formats,
lower case, PART-DET deleted, NOSUBENT for 002 - 007
and 043 - 059 (not relevant to EXFOR), REACTION
free text, ANALYSIS.

x4headers.headerHelp: Angle, laboratory system

x4freetext: The data were obtained by dividing the effective
double  differential cross section  by the sum
rule factor N*Z/A.
The neutron   spectra   obtained   at  bremsstrahlung
endpoint energies of 55 and 85 MeV  were  normalized
for  equal numbers of photons at the giant-resonance
peak energy.  The neutron  difference  spectrum  was
calculated by means of subtraction of 55-MeV neutron
spectrum from 85 MeV  neutron  spectrum. The  photon
difference spectrum was calculated as the difference
between 85- and 55-MeV bremsstrahlung  spectra.  The
effective  double  differential  cross  section  was
obtained by dividing the neutron difference spectrum
by the photon difference spectrum.
Statistical errors of measurement.
Data from Fig. 6.
Corrected by SD and VV: REACTION,
ANALYSIS, STATUS, EN-MIN, ERR-S.
